<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.chron.com/cs/CDA/ssistory.mpl/front/1891319">www.chron.com/cs/CDA/ssis...nt/1891319</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
Yes, it's a couple of months old, but does that make it any less evil, the idea of corporations and now governments taking out life insurance on old people just to make a buck when they die?  How sick is this?  Is dead peasant insurance in any way defensible? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1345<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/8/03 12:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Evil?  Or just a good business practice?</span><hr size=1> I have no problem with it.  If Ayiar wants to offer me a policy on the life of the cast of Chips and I want to enter into the contract, I see no reason we shouldn't be able to do so.  It's a contract, people can bet on anything they want.  If Kerai wants to offer me a contract by which I get 200 dozen chocolate chip cookies in the event that his dog dies from eating too much chocolate, it's no one else's business but ours.  The point is, however strange a contract may be, why should we care when it doesn't have any effect on us anyways?<br>
<br>
The case of a company insuring its employees is even more compelling.  If an employee dies, that represents a loss for the company financially, so there is no reason not to insure against it.<br>
<br>
