<br>
That's clearly different and not just business.<br>
<br>
In the private sector it's also different if the party buying the insurance does have some control over the likelihood of the person living or dying.  For instance, the ability to create an unsafe work environment.  It's not as pronounced a &quot;bad&quot; as it is with the government doing it, but certainly the public policy argument for prohibiting it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1359<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/8/03 4:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Evil?  Or just a good business practice?</span><hr size=1> If they create an unsafe work environment or do anything to actually endanger the lives of innocents, that's immoral.  If they just gamble on it, I don't see why anyone would be upset.<br>
