<br>
Insuring key employees, while employed is legit and always has been - as it's assumed you still have an incentive in keeping them healthy - there is no conflict of interest.  This is talking about &quot;insurance&quot; with no &quot;insurable interest&quot; where the company will only benefit from the death of what in many cases is a retired employee, whose death does not otherwise cause a loss. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1389<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(7/10/03 11:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=126.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Evil?  Or just a good business practice?</span><hr size=1> I don't care if companies do it, but why would they?  What incentive would you have to make a bet on an employee's life like that when the insurance company is stacking the odds against you?  I just don't get why you'd do it...<br>
